Lists

A list is an ordered collection of items that can hold multiple data types.

You create a list using square brackets [].

fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
mixed = ["Alice", 42, True, 3.14]

âœ… Accessing List Items


Use indexing to access elements:

print(fruits[0])  # apple
print(fruits[-1]) # cherry


âœ‚ï¸ Slicing Lists


Extract a part of a list:

print(fruits[1:3])  # ['banana', 'cherry']
print(numbers[:3])  # [1, 2, 3]

List Functions and Methods

Here are the most common list methods:

append(x)

Adds x to the end of the list

fruits.append("mango")

_________________________________

insert(i, x)

Inserts x at index i

fruits.insert(1, "kiwi")
_________________________________

remove(x)

Removes the first occurrence of x

fruits.remove("apple")

__________________________________

pop(i)

Removes and returns item at index i

fruits.pop(2)
__________________________________
clear()

Empties the list

fruits.clear()
____________________________________
index(x)

Returns index of first occurrence of x

fruits.index("banana")
_____________________________________
count(x)

Counts number of times x appears

fruits.count("apple")
________________________________________
reverse()

Reverses the list in-place

fruits.reverse()
_________________________________________
sort()

Sorts the list in-place

numbers.sort()


ğŸ”„ Examples in Action
fruits = ["apple", "banana"]
fruits.append("cherry")     # ['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']
fruits.insert(1, "kiwi")    # ['apple', 'kiwi', 'banana', 'cherry']
fruits.remove("banana")     # ['apple', 'kiwi', 'cherry']
popped = fruits.pop(0)      # popped = 'apple', fruits = ['kiwi', 'cherry']
fruits.reverse()            # ['cherry', 'kiwi']
